title = "Cutting Fluids and Coolant Management"

content = """
Cutting fluids perform several critical functions in machining operations: cooling the cutting zone to reduce tool wear and prevent workpiece thermal distortion, lubricating the chip-tool interface to reduce friction and built-up edge, flushing chips away from the cutting zone, and improving surface finish. At Ridgecrest Metalworks, cutting fluid selection and management are part of the quality and tooling cost control program.

Straight cutting oils (neat oils) are petroleum or synthetic oils without water dilution. They provide excellent lubrication but poor cooling. They are preferred for threading, tapping, broaching, and gear cutting where lubrication is more critical than cooling. They are used with lower-speed operations on difficult materials like stainless steel.

Soluble (emulsifiable) oils are petroleum oils with emulsifying agents that dilute with water to produce milky emulsions. They provide good cooling and moderate lubrication and are the most widely used type in general machining. Concentration (ratio of oil to water) is typically 5–10% oil for most operations, adjusted upward for more demanding cuts. Concentration must be checked with a refractometer at the start of each shift and when makeup water is added.

Synthetic and semi-synthetic fluids use chemical compounds rather than petroleum oils. They provide excellent cooling, good rust protection, better biological stability (longer sump life), and easy cleaning. They are common in CNC machining centers where long sump life and consistent concentration are important.

Coolant sump management is essential. Metal chips, tramp oil (hydraulic and way oil contamination), and bacterial growth degrade fluid performance and create health hazards (dermatitis, respiratory irritation). Sump maintenance includes: daily chip removal, weekly sump cleaning in high-production machines, regular addition of biocide to prevent bacterial blooms, refractometer concentration checks, and pH monitoring (pH should remain 8.5–9.5 for most synthetics). Fluid must be disposed of through licensed waste disposal services; it cannot be discharged to sewer or storm drains.

Operators must use appropriate PPE (nitrile gloves, safety glasses) when handling concentrated coolants. Mist suppression or enclosure is required on high-speed machining centers to prevent inhalation of aerosols.
"""

version = "0.0.1"
